          "type": "text",
          "text": "1. Overview"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "ConvertOverpunch4ToInt32",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " function is a scalar function in Microsoft SQL Server designed to convert a specific type of numeric representation known as \"overpunch\" into a standard 32-bit integer. Overpunch is a method used in legacy systems, particularly in mainframe environments, to encode both the numeric value and the sign of a number within a single character. This function interprets a 4-character overpunch string and converts it into an integer."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "2. Complexity Level: Medium"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The complexity level of this function is medium. While the logic for converting overpunch characters is straightforward, understanding the overpunch encoding scheme requires specialized knowledge. The function must correctly interpret the overpunch character to determine the sign and value of the number, which involves conditional logic and character manipulation."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "3. Input Parameters"
